.TH WHEREAMI 1 "July 2026" "whereami 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
whereami \- determine the current shell environment
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B whereami
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B whereami
displays information about the current shell session, including the
shell name, version, process ID, executable path, and whether the shell
is interactive and supports command history.
.PP
It supports a wide range of shells: bash, zsh, fish, ksh, dash, ash, sh,
tcsh, csh, yash, and others. It uses multiple detection methods:
.PP
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Checking shell-specific environment variables
.IP \(bu
Examining the /proc/$$/exe symlink (on Linux)
.IP \(bu
Using the ps command to inspect the process tree
.IP \(bu
Falling back to the basename of $0
.IP \(bu
Looking at the parent process if all else fails
.RE
.PP
The output is plain text, suitable for scripts and debugging.
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
$ whereami
Shell: fish
Version: 3.6.0
PID: 12345
Executable: /usr/bin/fish
Interactive: yes
History: available
.fi
